Field Label:
Some young people have times when they are energetic, or cheerful, very different from how they usually feel.  At these times, they may also feel more talkative, more active, sleep less and feel more restless.


CURRENT/MOST RECENT EPISODE
So you said that you had a time when you've felt (more active, excited, energetic):
Do you feel this way now?
How old were you the last time you felt this way?
How long did you feel this way?
How old were you when this ended?
If now, how long have you felt this way?
Was there a time that was more intense or lasted longer than this time?
How old were you when you felt this way?
How long did you feel this way?
How old were you when this ended?
INTERVIEWER: Code the most intense episode.

SYMPTOMS


MOOD

Now I would like to talk to you about that time.
Feel really, really happy or excited much more than usual?
Was this just during holiday or fun situations, which normally make people your age excited?
Feel grouchy, cranky, or irritable? When the smallest things would make you really mad?
Did you get through your school work much more easily or faster than usual?
Did you spend much more time with your friends or were you going out more than usual?
Were you more involved with your family?
INTERVIEWER: Use discretion on whether to ask child next question.
Were you interested in sex more than usual, or more sexually active?
Did you do more physical activities?
Were you really restless or did you have trouble sitting still?
How many hours of sleep do you usually get per night?
During this time, how many hours, on average, do you sleep per night?
Did you feel rested even though you slept less than usual?
If no change in hours from normal:
Were you able to do more activities than usual with the same amount of sleep?
Did you talk more than usual?
Did you feel you just couldn't stop talking?
Did you talk faster than usual?
Did people have trouble understanding you or try to get you to talk slower?
Did your thoughts go faster than usual?
So fast it was hard to keep up with them?
Did they race through your head?
Did they make sense to you?
Did they make sense to other people?
Did other people have trouble following what you were saying?
Did you have too many thoughts jumping through your mind?
Did you have problems concentrating, or get distracted very easily?
Did you keep noticing things that you would've normally ignored?
Did you have trouble keeping your mind on things?
Did it interfere with schoolwork or reading?
Was this so much of a problem that other people noticed?
Did you feel more confident in yourself than usual?
Did you feel like you could do anything?
Did you feel you were a very important person?
Did you feel like you had abilities that made you more special, smarter, or better than other people?
Did you do things that you usually wouldn't do, or did you do things that you later wished you hadn't done? For example, did you:
Spend or borrow a lot of money?
Do things that could get you into trouble?
Do things from which you might get hurt?
Make a lot of telephone calls or call people at strange hours?
You just told me that when you felt (more active) that you also had (list symptoms).  How often did you have these things?
Choices, Calculations, OR Slider Labels: 1, Most days | 2, About half of the days | 3, Less than half the days | 9, Don't know

Field Label: On the days you had these things, how much of the day did you have them?
Choices, Calculations, OR Slider Labels: 1, All of the day | 2, Most of the day | 3, Half of the day | 4, Only a little part of the day

Field Label:
DEPRESSIVE SYMPTOMS

During this period, did you also feel/have...?  (As I list these other symptoms, please recall if you have ever had any of them at the same time.)
INTERVIEWER: Refer to Course Patterns Card.
INTERVIEWER: If no, SKIP to Psychosis Episode.
CHANGES IN MOTOR ACTIVITY OR MOVEMENT:
Did you think that someone was trying to harm you?
Did you think that you had powers or abilities that others did not have?
Did you think that you had a special mission?
Did you believe things that other people didn't think were true?

INTERVIEWER: Based on clinical judgment, were these 
real delusions? Get examples.
INTERVIEWER:If not real delusions, SKIP to Hallucinations.
Did you start thinking these things before, after, or at the same time that you started feeling (too active /happy /excited/grouchy /energetic)?
Did you think this was true, even when you stopped feeling (too happy/excited/grouchy/energetic).
For how long did you think this was true?

During this time, did you see or hear things that other people could not see or hear?
PROBE: Like voices talking to you or noises, or visions?
Did you experience funny or unusual smells, tastes, or sensations in your body?
INTERVIEWER:Based on clinical judgment, were these real hallucinations? Get examples.
INTERVIEWER: If not really hallucinations, SKIP to Mood Congruency.
Did these (list endorsed hallucinations) start before, after or at the same time that you started feeling (too happy/excited/grouchy/energetic)?
Did they stay even when you stopped feeling (too happy/excited/grouchy/energetic)?
For how long did you have them?

INTERVIEWER: If respondent had any psychotic symptoms, was the content consistent with manic themes such as inflated worth, power, knowledge, identity or special relationship with a deity or famous person.

ASSOCIATED CONDITIONS (EPISODE)

INTERVIEWER: Associated condition questions apply ONLY to episode being coded.



MEDICAL

Did you have a serious physical problem or illness?

(Probe: Did the physical problem or illness start before you started feeling (too happy/excited/grouchy/energetic) or after?)

Were you taking any medicines that your doctor told you to take? Did you take any over the counter medications?

PROBE: Did you start to feel (too happy/excited/grouchy/energetic) before taking the medicine or after?

Were you using alcohol often or drugs or both during this time?  

PROBE: Did you start feeling this way before using alcohol/drugs or after or did you increase the quantity after you had these feelings?

I want to know how your feeling (too happy/excited/grouchy/energetic) and other symptoms caused problems for you.

Please look at the scale.
INTERVIEWER: Remind child how to use scale, if necessary, and assess areas most pertinent to the disorder; e.g. family, school, peers.

 Who did you get help from the first time?
